    <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
      <p>The League of Women Voters is a non-partisan volunteer organization whose purpose is to promote political responsibility through the informed and active participation of citizens in government. The League's major activity is voter education; before most elections the League publishes a Voters Guide with information about the candidates and the various ballot proposals. The League also takes action is support of, or in opposition to, selected governmental issues. It does not support or oppose candidates, nor does it support or oppose political parties.</p>
      <p>The Allen Park League was organized as a provisional league in 1955; in 1956 this provisional association was formally recognized as the League of Women Voters of Allen Park. In 1984 the Allen Park League investigated the possibility of merging with the Dearborn-Dearborn Heights League but decided against this action. In 1986, however, the Allen Park League ceased to operate as an independent chapter, merging instead with the Downriver Wayne County League of Women Voters which comprised League chapters from the towns of Southgate, Riverview, Trenton, Woodhaven, Wyandotte, and Grosse Ile.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
      <p>The records of the Allen Park League of Women Voters consist of annual meeting and board meeting minutes and reports, 1955-1986; member newsletters, 1955-1986; topical files comprising committee minutes, reports, position statements, correspondence, pamphlets, and other publications. Subjects covered by files include municipal, county, state, and national elections, and social, political, and environmental issues. The records have been arranged into two series: Administrative Files and Topical Files. Although a wide range of issues of concern to the League's members in the 1960s and 1970s are represented in these files, the documentation of local politics and elections, social services, and environmental issues is particularly strong. As such, these files provide a detailed account of the issues raised by the growth of Allen Park from a small village into a suburban city between 1955 and 1986.</p>
    </scopecontent>
